{{Infobox philosopher |<!-- Scroll down to edit this page --> <!-- Philosopher Category --> region = Continental Philosophy |era = [[20th-century philosophy]] |color = #B0C4DE |
<!-- Image and Caption --> <!-- image = .jpg| -->
<!-- Information --> name = Herbert Spiegelberg |birth_date = May 18, 1904 |birth_place = [[Straßburg]], [[Alsace-Lorraine]], [[German Empire]] |death_date = {{d-da|September 6, 1990|May 18, 1904}} |death_place = [[St. Louis, Missouri]] |school_tradition = [[phenomenology (philosophy)|Phenomenology]] |main_interests = [[Continental Philosophy|Contemporary continental philosophy]], [[History of ideas]], [[Ethics]], [[Phenomenological psychology]] |influences = [[Edmund Husserl]] |influenced = Growth of phenomenology in North America in second half of 20th century }}
'''Herbert Spiegelberg''' (May 18, 1904 &ndash; September 6, 1990) was an [[United States|American]] [[philosopher]] who played a prominent role in the advancement of the [[phenomenology (philosophy)|phenomenogical movement]] in the United States.
==Life==
Spiegelberg was born in [[Strasbourg]], in the [[Alsace|Alsatian]] region of northeastern [[France]]. He studied at the universities of [[University of Heidelberg|Heidelberg]], [[University of Freiburg|Freiburg]], and [[University of Munich|Munich]], where he encountered [[Edmund Husserl]] and many others in the vanguard of the European phenomenological movement. He received his [[Ph.D.]] in 1928 from the University of Munich. His doctoral dissertation was written under the direction of the phenomenologist [[Alexander Pfänder]] and was titled ''Gesetz und Sittengesetz'' (''Law and Morality'').
In 1937 Spiegelberg left the continent and studied for a year in England before emigrating to the United States. In the U. S., he taught first at [[Swarthmore College]] and then at [[Lawrence University]], which later awarded him an honorary doctoral degree.
In 1953-54 and 1955-56 he received grants from the [[Rockefeller Foundation]] for the preparation of the first edition of his landmark historical survey, ''The Phenomenological Movement: A Historical Introduction''.
In 1963, he relocated to [[Washington University in St. Louis]], [[Missouri]] and remained there until his retirement as [[Emeritus Professor]] in 1971. He also served as visiting professor at the universities of [[University of Michigan|Michigan]] and [[University of Southern California|Southern California]] and as [[Fulbright program|Fulbright]] Lecturer at the University of Munich.
Spiegelberg conducted five influential workshops in phenomenology, during the summers of 1965, 1966, 1967, 1969, and 1972. The first workshop was supported by a grant from the [[National Science Foundation]] and the second by a grant from the [[Monsanto Company]].
In 1981 Washington University established a [http://artsci.wustl.edu/~philos/history/lectures.htm series of lectures in phenomenology] in his honor.
Herbert Spiegelberg died of [[leukemia]], at the age of 86, at his home in St. Louis, Missouri. His collected papers are available in the [http://archon.wulib.wustl.edu/index.php?p=collections/findingaid&id=367&q=sturgis&rootcontentid=479782 archives of the Washington University Libraries].
==Philosophy== {{Expand section|date=June 2008}}
Spiegelberg played a major role in the development of interest in phenomenology in America.
