'''''History, Labour, and Freedom: Themes from Marx''''' is a 1988 book by the philosopher [[Gerald Cohen]].

==Summary==
{{cleanup section||reason=Section is currently based on secondary sources discussing the work. It should be based principally on the book itself|date=June 2018}}
''History, Labour, and Freedom'' is a revision and expansion of Cohen's earlier ''[[Karl Marx's Theory of History: A Defence]]'' (1978).{{sfn|McLellan|1995|page=440}} The work reprints several papers that argue against the idea that [[libertarianism]] advances freedom.{{sfn|Wolff|1991|page=154}}

==Reception==
===Mainstream media===
''History, Labour, and Freedom'' was reviewed by the political scientist [[David McLellan (political scientist)|David McLellan]] in ''[[The Times Literary Supplement]]''.{{sfn|McLellan|1989|page=809}}

===Academic journals===
''History, Labour, and Freedom'' received a positive review from McLellan in ''Political Studies''.{{sfn|McLellan|1990|page=756}} The book was also reviewed by William H. Shaw in ''[[Inquiry: Critical Thinking Across the Disciplines|Inquiry]]'',{{sfn|Shaw|1989|pages=437–453}} Daniel Little in ''[[Political Theory (journal)|Political Theory]]'',{{sfn|Little|1990|pages=312–315}} and Andrew Levine in ''[[The Journal of Philosophy]]''.{{sfn|Levine|1991|pages=267–275}}

McLellan credited Cohen with "lucidity and sharpness of argument", and with offering important reformulations of the theory of historical revisionism put forward in ''Karl Marx's Theory of History: A Defence'' (1978). He considered Cohen's "discussion of the strength of nonmaterial
cultural elements such as religion and nationalism" particularly interesting, and found Cohen's discussion of the questions of how capitalism should be overcome, what form socialist society should take, and "the practical implications of the changing nature of the working class" to be "stimulating and relevant".{{sfn|McLellan|1990|page=756}}

